tool.name: RegressionPlot

param.name: date_to_generate
param.dialogReference:
The date to generate the regression.

Note: time does not matter in the selection.

param.name: gain_setting
param.dialogReference: What setting do you want to use for the regression? Only valid gain settings for a given data are populated in the dropdown menu.

param.name: depths
param.dialogReference: Click box to use all vertical profile records regard less of depth. The default is to use only the records in the top meter of the water column but not all vertical profiles have data for this area.

param.name: preview
param.dialogReference:
Generate a quick preview of the regression plot. Plot should open automatically. If the plot fails to generate, that means that either all the sites for the grab and vertical profiles didn't match or that there are no records within the top meter of the depth column

Plot can also be found at arcproject\plots\chl_regression_tool_preview.png (this gets overwritten)

Note: there is a slight delay after checking the box since R generates the preview. Be patient - clicking the box again before the preview is generated can cause the ArcMap document to crash.

param.name: output
param.dialogReference:
Path to location to save the output graph.

File extension should end in ".png"

param.name: commit
param.dialogReference:
Add regression info to the database to use for the Chl correction?

This well append the regression R-square value and coefficients to the regression table in the database and use them when correcting the chl values for the water quality transects.

Note: this tool only appends new records, if there already exists records for a given date and regression setting the tool will return an error. Please delete any existing regression info from the data base before updating a given date.

tool.summary:
Generates a plot showing water grab Chl values and vertical profile Chl values with a linear regression.

Select a date that has both vertical profiles and lab values. Use the Rename grab + profiles for given date tool to fix site names before running the tool since the site names are used to join the two datasets together.

Dates will valid data will show the gain setting options. Once the gain and date are selected, you can then generate a plot preview and choose to include all depths (by default only depths in the top 1m of the water column are used).

Running the tool will save a copy of the plot to the output location specified and optionally commit the regression information to the data base (note: this will not overwrite any existing data in the database so make sure to delete any exisiting regression info for a given date and gain setting if re-running a regression).
